The 900-page report was leaked to local media and first reported by Nepali tabloid Jana Aastha on Wednesday, two weeks after its submission to the interim government. The leak comes as Nepal prepares to swear in a new government on Friday amid criticisms that the current government, led by interim Prime Minister Sushila Karki, has kept the report under wraps.

“The Nepal government must now officially make the investigation public so that we know the veracity of the full report,” said Pradip Gwayali, a youth activist. “From the leaked report, we know that it has explained the events of September 8 in detail, but it did not delve into what unfolded on September 9. That should be fully investigated, too.”

